<br>
Paladin's armor drop in planes -- will occur....now and then, will occur in singles, will require you to hit Fear 20, maybe 30 times before you have acquired -half- the suit.  (/rips his hair out) (I was lucky to complete my set around Fear raid 11 or 13..can't recal any more)<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
All in all, though, I like paladins and their ability to heal.  The argument always stands as to how good your character is...well, thats up to you, and how well you want to make him.  This requires playing strategy, such as the use of shield buffs for your group members, not just for yourself, using your taunt skill and stun spells to pull aggro on to yourself rather than letting the main tank take all of the damage, knowing when to LoH the first member to reach 1 bubble of health to keep them alive -- sacrifice that LoH for another group member.  I'm shocked, and pissed, even at my level to see paladins save their LoH for themselves like greedy little peons, when a group member is dieing.  <br>
<br>
Armor matters more so for us I would say than warriors.  Warriors seem to have it made on the ac, Indocilite seems to always have 5-15 ac more per item vs. Vallorium. (Vallorium bp is 30 ac...Indocilite is somewhere over 40 ac..I'm pretty sure on that 40, might be right around that value).  Your haste item matters greatly, as does your weapon.  Grab a high ac shield, save up for it if you have to (or become Erudite, and acquire the Maestro shield from Hate), and get the tops in haste items.  My oppinion on worth would be CoF or CoCW.  Both are superb ac, stats, and haste (36%), but CoCW offers 50mana vs. CoF's 50 hp.  And you want the mana-- again, my preference, since you can cast, the extra mana is as good as your  60damage 5 second stun.  So, get your armor, its possible to surpass 1000ac, I did it myself recently, and its VERY nice...get a tops haste item (attend the raids,  it'll drop, you'll get it, or the scale...and acquire that weapon that offers the quickest hitting with best damage result.  Shields are a must until epic (but don't include epic on your decision...epics are a pain in the butt).<br>
<br>
Being a paladin allows you to step back from battle and act as a back up cleric when the true cleric is down, or, to equip your wisdom gear and sit out of the battles and med for heals, when you are the only cleric-type in the group.  I've noticed this more and more once I reached level 54.  Level 57 opens the gates for an even better ability to heal, with a spell dumping nearly 600 hp in to a target.  And you get rez with xp, eventually.  The latter examples are something to look forward to, something to work up to.<br>
<br>
I'd fill a group with paladins any day.  2-4 pally's will always ensure you will have a good time.  It's fun and challenging...when it comes down to a last minute decision on rooting the mob and medding (or using your DW Helm to keep the group members alive with the 100hp continuous buff).  <br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
SK's -- I don't know an awful lot about this class.  My experiences have been on planar raids and in groups with friends that are this class.  Post 50 is when SK Pet's (yes, they get a skeleton) is worth a lick.  The fact that they get to conjure a pet as a necro does, equip it with a weapon (and I've heard post 50, at some point, you can equip with 2?..unsure), is great.  I've seen peeps in LGuk use their pet to take the Harm Touch from the Ghoul Lord ((oh my, is that the name? It's been so long now hehe...Lord Room, where Yak drops).  Later on, SK's get the ability to summon corpses, so when you are hunting for a necro to get your corpse out of a deep zone...well, you don't need to any more.  SK's get dots, life taps, 2 spell bases that are tops in my book, because I always like to rely on dots, even in planes.  Life taps are aken to heals, although perhaps less powerful, the ability is still there.  Their Harm Touch which can be invoked, is a very nice skill to have -- I'm unsure, but pre-50 HT does maybe 500? 750? damage.  Unsure on that.  <br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Both classes can only single wield.  Both classes get some seriously nice weapons in 1h and 2h choice.  There are some 'must have' weapons for both classes.  Sword of the Mourning is a must have for paladins, and my oppinion, Mace of Shadowed Souls is a must have for SK's.  Both are similar in damage/delay.  <br>
<br>
SK's really do get an easier chance at planar loot once you are 46+.<br>
<br>
Paladins can tank nearly as well as Warriors.  Warriors will have more HP at base, prior to buffs, but that warrior is also wailing on the mob more often, with their dual wield death-wish.  Paladin's, at level 54, have the ability to transfer aggro from the main tank when a life-threatening situation occurs for the warrior or another group member, merely by the spells they have at their disposal.  Stun, Force, Might, and a flame based DD will total 275 damage and a roughly 5 seconds of stun on a mob, definitely in time to piss them off and keep the aggro on you.  If your warrior is dieing...this is prime.  And if LoH is up, warrior shouldn't die, as the LoH will heal a good portion of that boy's hp's.  The stun spells you begin acquiring I -think- after level 22...or perhaps its 30.  I honestly didn't learn the true good of passing aggro to me until I went in to the hole with a friend and my group.  She explained how paladins can use their stuns consecutively to grab the mob's attention.  I wish I had known that 20 levels ago.  But in any case...the stuns are prime for paladins.  And that 125dd?  Ahhhhh, yes!<br>
<br>
Paladin's can tack on an additional ...hmm...850'ish hp and 30-40'ish ac by buffs once level 53.  His buffs help beginning at level 9, but the mana is so little, he will have trouble keeping the group buffed if he is to fight.  The mana starts evening out once you pass level 40.  At level 49 you get some seriously balancing buffs for the class, with the onset of Armor of Faith and a couple others.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Hope that helps some.  I'm biased towards Paladin's because I play one.  But I wouldn't hold it against an SK to tank as well as myself.  I&quot;m sure they can come close, if not equal a paladin.<br>
<br>
One thing -- as you gain level, you will notice that your hunting grounds will generally be much nearer to good cities rather than evil cities.  But /shrug, that doesn't much matter in the long haul.<br>
<br>
