<br>
First, as Moonfray said, we are half necro, half warrior. We receive a skeleton pet. However, this pet will never be more than half your level, often much lower... Until level 58. The vast majority of our pets serve two purposes: First, it's a DoT you only have to cast when it dies. Second, it's great for giving a party that extra 5 seconds of 'Run away, run away' time.. This all changes with the 49  pets, which begin to duel wield, have enough hit points to take a few lickings and keep on ticking.. The level 58 pet, which is the 44 necro spell, summons what is considered to be one of the very best necro pets, and is capable of doing things like lifetapping and camping upper guk, all on its very own. <br>
<br>
We receive Lifetaps. These aren't really used as heals until the highest levels, mmm... Drain Soul... as they simply don't take enough. They're better used so that the healer of the party has the time to heal the caster before she's forced to deal with you. <br>
<br>
We receive DoTs. Much like the pet, they are severely under level. They won't really do noticeable damage to a mob your own level, again, until the very highest levels. However, even at the lower levels, they let us do exactly what we do better than anyone else in the game.. Taunt. Shadowknights begin to get level appropriate dots, again, in the 50  game, beginning with Dooming Darkness at 49, as well as Boil Blood, Cascading Darkness and Asystole(Spelling?) later on.<br>
<br>
A shadow knight can out taunt any other class in the game, with the proper combination of spells. There's something about multiple debuffs and DoTs combined with fast, hard, hits that just really, really irks a mob off. Generally, when I feel it's worth the effort, I can keep a mob glued on me. A chain stunning paladin can usually peel it off me, for about 6 seconds, when the next pulse of all three DoTs hits, and it remembers just why it hates me. <br>
<br>
Again, at the higher levels, we begin to gain the ability to buff our attack and AC ratings directly, draining the strength and toughness from our enemies. Unlike the paladin buffs, these buffs will stack with high end cleric buffs, and it's not uncommon for me to be buffed by 101 AC points between the cleric, ranger, and myself. <br>
<br>
Even in the lower levels, a Shadow Knight is one of the few melee types that can be expected to solo effectively, with the ability to both snare(Darkness) and Fear. While it certainly can be messy, it is more reliable than root/heal. <br>
<br>
Unlike the paladin or warrior, we are built for stealth as well, as much so as the necro or the enchanter. With a short casting self-invis, and invis to undead, we can get places with an ease that other melee classes(excepting the rogue) can only dream of.<br>
<br>
And then, there is the last important ability of a Shadow Knight. At level 30, we gain the spell Feign Death... I'm sure I don't need to expound upon the miracle that is FD to a warrior.  <br>
<br>
However, for all this high end miracle working, we have to battle our way through 40 or 50 levels of, well, sucking. You will, as either a paladin or a SK do less damage than a warrior. You will have fewer hit points, and unless you have the best of gear, less AC. Further, with the lack of self healing, buffs, etc, with a good portion of your offense being such that an enchanter cannot mez something you're fighting to make breathing room, the lack of blending in your spell book, a mid level SK has very little room for error. Harm touch, your emergency damage/taunt button, begins to fall off in value at about level 30, until around level 50. Pre 40, it does Level*10 1 damage., post 40 it goes up 30 point a level.<br>
<br>
Basically, though, the worth of an SK is entirely dependant upon the skill of the person behind it: A well played, well geared SK is a god of death capable of wreaking havoc anywhere, anywhen, with help or without(/grovel Starseed!). A competent, single SK can still bring a great deal to a group, although a paladin might bring more, and paladins certainly don't suffer as much loss of efficiency when there are even more paladins in the party. An incompetent SK is the first to die. <br>
<br>
In summary, the path of a Shadow Knight is as harsh and cruel as the man or woman that walks it, but the rewards at the end of that path are very great indeed.  <p><center>Arathena Dracheseele<br>
