<br>
1: AC/HP. These are two sides of the same coin, and serve only one purpose: To let you meat shield a touch longer. You'll have to strike your own balance between them, it's something you run by feel. However, be forewarned. These numbers will only begin to approach a warriors with the very best of gear. Despite our recent gain in Defensive skill, our armor is of poorer quality than the equivalent warrior gear. You will also have fewer hit points, although there have also been vast improvements from the days of Rogue-like HP and AC. <br>
<br>
2: Mana. This is what, in theory, will allow you to make up for your weakness in HP and AC. This includes Int/Wis, and  Mana gear. Although we no longer have a smaller mana pool than our parent classes, we still pay more per spell casting, as we obtain the same spells at a higher level. Further, as Hybrids, we never gain the ability to specialize, meaning that we will always pay the full, inflated, mana cost for our spells. Also, since you will be throwing yourself into the fray with both body and words, your time to meditate is drastically reduced, and the size of your mana pool must be sufficient to cover for this. <br>
<br>
3: Resists. Other than raids, these are more or less pointless. Magic is the only one that the important spells, such as slow, snare, etc, check against, and these days, I've been praying that the mob takes the time to start casting Ice comet at me... It's 6 seconds that he's not wailing at me with his 80 damage, 10 delay fists. However, you will have to pay a little attention to your MR, as you do not gain the level bonus to any of your resists that a warrior does to his MR. <br>
<br>
Hrm, that's about all I can think of, and it shouldn't be much different from any experience you might have as a warrior. <br>
