itle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/9/01 12:34:02 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Paladins VS Shadowknights. advice please</span><hr size=1> The one thing that has not been mentioned here is the SK Soloing abilities. Pull with a Darkness series spell to snare/DoT/Blind, Sick pet on MoB (gives one time for next spell), Fear, DoT some more, chase the enemy wacking on him until he is dead. SK's should be able to Fear Kite enemies like this that are yellow all day long. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Note: </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> DO NOT attempt this in a dungeon. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Another tip for playing an SK is always type &quot;/pet taunt off&quot; as soon as you create a pet. Also, I never arm a pet or Fear Kite yellows until I know the pet can take a few hits. <br>
<br>
If you are fighting casters in a group, take along a couple of cheap shields and a blunt (or a Gnoll Whip) and equip your pet with these. Even the lowest level pets can shield bash effectively. Otherwise, equip the pet with the heaviest damage two-hander you can find.<br>
<br>
The SK Snare (Darkness series) is a taunt/DoT/Blindness that outclasses Ranger and Druid Snare. I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> always</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> insist on snaring is a group. The Ranger/Druid Snare with overwrite the SK/Necro Darkness so all other Snarers must be made aware of this. <br>
<br>
Another hint is to make two hot keys for your primary and secondary pallets. One should say &quot;/pet attack&quot; and the other &quot;/pet back off&quot;. This way you can control the pet in battle. Also, sometimes it is easier to assist the pet then to try to get it to switch targets. Finally, pulling for a group with a pet up is next to impossable.<br>
<br>
The only other thing I can think of that was not mentioned about SK's is that at level 9 we get Locate Corpse. This comes in very handy.<br>
